<div class="paragraph">The StraightFlo Valve is a drop in replacement valve for&nbsp;industrial reciprocating compressors, for speeds from 200 rpm to over 3600 rpm,&nbsp;pressure differential across a valve to 4350 psi (300 bar), service temperatures from -290F (-180C)&nbsp; to 482F(250C), and for all gases including sweet and sour natural gas, acid gas, CO2, Hydrogen, Nitrogen, Ethylene, Air, Ammonia, HCl, etc.<br /><br />The StraightFlo Valve is patented in several countries world-wide. It is a revolutionary, reciprocating compressor valve technology that results in step improvements in valve key&nbsp;performance indicators through its unique design:<br /><br />1. Reduced power losses. 10% measured lower compressor power in a pipeline&nbsp;transmission compressor running&nbsp;at 1000 rpm. or&nbsp;a 10% increase&nbsp;in compressor flow for the same power. Reduction in power improves with&nbsp;increase in&nbsp;speed, high molecular weight gases, where the gas quality is bad, where conventional valves experience flutter during operation and where the valve has to operate over a wide range of operating conditions.<br />2. Reliability and life improvement of at least 2&nbsp;times&nbsp;that of the existing valves under the same conditions.<br />3. Valve turn around time of about 5 - 10&nbsp;minutes on site without any special tools, skilled labor, or&nbsp;machining. Never replace your valve seat or carrier.<br />4. Reduction in valve inventory by more than&nbsp;80%<br />5. Step&nbsp;improvement in tolerance towards liquids and solids&nbsp;in gas stream. Highly suitable for shale gas applications.<br />6. Significant reduction in emissions during compressor operation due the elimination of several shut downs for valve service. Each of these shutdowns results in significant emissions due to escape of gas from the compressor and adjacent pipeline and the need to flare/purge/blow down the pipeline for every such shutdown.<br />7.&nbsp;Reductions in emissions and&nbsp;Carbon footprint by 10% or more with just a change in valves.</div>

